WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.916 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.916 --> 00:00:04.311 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.311 --> 00:00:07.664 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.664 --> 00:00:10.690 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.690 --> 00:00:15.530 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So last time, we
talked about Dirac equation.

00:00:15.530 --> 00:00:23.225 align:middle line:84%
So the Dirac equation
has the following form:

00:00:23.225 --> 00:00:29.490 align:middle line:84%
gamma mu partial mu
minus m psi equal to 0.

00:00:29.490 --> 00:00:32.570 align:middle line:90%


00:00:32.570 --> 00:00:35.100 align:middle line:90%
So here, we have two spaces.

00:00:35.100 --> 00:00:43.190 align:middle line:84%
So one is your standard physical
spacetime, so with x mu.

00:00:43.190 --> 00:00:45.680 align:middle line:84%
And then we have a
lot of internal space

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:51.300 align:middle line:84%
which is labeled by the index
of the psi and the gamma,

00:00:51.300 --> 00:00:52.970 align:middle line:90%
which has suppressed here.

00:00:52.970 --> 00:00:55.385 align:middle line:84%
So psi should be considered
as a four vector.

00:00:55.385 --> 00:00:58.220 align:middle line:90%


00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:01.840 align:middle line:84%
So alpha equal to 1,
2, 3, 4, and the gamma

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:07.900 align:middle line:84%
mu should be considered
as a matrix--

00:01:07.900 --> 00:01:11.200 align:middle line:90%
a 4x4 matrix.

00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:15.740 align:middle line:84%
And so this space
labeled by alpha--

00:01:15.740 --> 00:01:17.365 align:middle line:84%
so this is called
the spinor space.

00:01:17.365 --> 00:01:23.320 align:middle line:90%


00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:24.770 align:middle line:90%
This is called spinor space.

00:01:24.770 --> 00:01:27.850 align:middle line:84%
So you have to be
careful that now we

00:01:27.850 --> 00:01:31.510 align:middle line:84%
have two spaces
intertwined together.

00:01:31.510 --> 00:01:34.240 align:middle line:84%
One is your ordinary
spacetime, and so this

00:01:34.240 --> 00:01:39.130 align:middle line:84%
is a function of the spacetime,
but it's carried on index--

00:01:39.130 --> 00:01:41.330 align:middle line:90%
yeah, carries on indices.

00:01:41.330 --> 00:01:44.750 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
matrix equation.

00:01:44.750 --> 00:01:48.970 align:middle line:84%
So altogether, there
are four equations here

00:01:48.970 --> 00:01:50.710 align:middle line:90%
for each component of psi.

00:01:50.710 --> 00:01:54.730 align:middle line:90%


00:01:54.730 --> 00:01:57.210 align:middle line:90%
And yeah, so let me pull--

00:01:57.210 --> 00:01:59.120 align:middle line:84%
let me just write
this a little better.

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:00.805 align:middle line:90%
So this is x--

00:02:00.805 --> 00:02:03.730 align:middle line:90%


00:02:03.730 --> 00:02:07.680 align:middle line:84%
let me call this equation
1, which I will use later.

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:10.185 align:middle line:84%
And this gamma mu, they
are not ordinary matrices.

00:02:10.185 --> 00:02:13.150 align:middle line:90%
They satisfy this condition.

00:02:13.150 --> 00:02:20.125 align:middle line:84%
Gamma mu, the anticommutator
with nu equal to 2 eta mu nu.

00:02:20.125 --> 00:02:22.630 align:middle line:90%


00:02:22.630 --> 00:02:28.090 align:middle line:84%
So that means different gamma
matrices when they are indexed

00:02:28.090 --> 00:02:29.600 align:middle line:90%
are not the same.

00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:32.380 align:middle line:84%
They anticommute
with each other.

00:02:32.380 --> 00:02:36.100 align:middle line:84%
So if you pass them through,
you get a minus sign.

00:02:36.100 --> 00:02:37.870 align:middle line:84%
So they anticommute
with each other

00:02:37.870 --> 00:02:40.930 align:middle line:84%
because when mu not equal to
nu, the right-hand side is 0.

00:02:40.930 --> 00:02:45.250 align:middle line:84%
And when you pass through
each other, you get the minus.

00:02:45.250 --> 00:02:47.240 align:middle line:90%
And the square of them--

00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:50.740 align:middle line:84%
so gamma 0 square, you get
minus 1 because this is 0, 0.

00:02:50.740 --> 00:02:51.550 align:middle line:90%
It's minus 1.

00:02:51.550 --> 00:02:54.610 align:middle line:84%
And the gamma i squared,
you just get one.

00:02:54.610 --> 00:02:56.780 align:middle line:90%
So this is very simple.

00:02:56.780 --> 00:02:57.690 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:02:57.690 --> 00:02:59.482 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: When you say
gamma i squared is 1,

00:02:59.482 --> 00:03:01.298 align:middle line:84%
you mean like its
the identity matrix?

00:03:01.298 --> 00:03:02.840 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
its identity matrix.

00:03:02.840 --> 00:03:06.290 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, when I say gamma
0 square is minus 1,

00:03:06.290 --> 00:03:08.370 align:middle line:84%
it's also minus times
identity matrix.

00:03:08.370 --> 00:03:10.990 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, exactly.

00:03:10.990 --> 00:03:17.280 align:middle line:84%
And also not all
gamma mu are Hermitian

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:19.650 align:middle line:84%
So the relation is
that the gamma mu

00:03:19.650 --> 00:03:25.605 align:middle line:84%
dagger is equal to gamma
0 gamma mu gamma 0.

00:03:25.605 --> 00:03:28.290 align:middle line:90%


00:03:28.290 --> 00:03:31.070 align:middle line:90%
So again, from here, you can--

00:03:31.070 --> 00:03:35.910 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so this is just a compact
way to write its properties.

00:03:35.910 --> 00:03:39.800 align:middle line:84%
When you have-- when
mu is equal to 0--

00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:44.960 align:middle line:84%
and then you have gamma 0 times
gamma 0 squared is minus 1.

00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:47.660 align:middle line:84%
And then you get the minus gamma
0-- tells you that the gamma

00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:50.160 align:middle line:90%
0 is anti-Hermitian.

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:52.980 align:middle line:84%
And if you take the
index to be i here,

00:03:52.980 --> 00:03:55.140 align:middle line:90%
and then you have index i here--

00:03:55.140 --> 00:03:58.140 align:middle line:84%
and then when 0 and
i-- they are not

00:03:58.140 --> 00:03:59.580 align:middle line:90%
the same, so they anticommute.

00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:02.700 align:middle line:84%
You can pass through this
gamma 0 through this gamma i.

00:04:02.700 --> 00:04:06.450 align:middle line:84%
You get the minus sign, and
then gamma 0 square gives you

00:04:06.450 --> 00:04:08.940 align:middle line:84%
another minus
sign, so you get 1.

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:12.150 align:middle line:84%
So that means that the gamma
i dagger equal to gamma i.

00:04:12.150 --> 00:04:13.830 align:middle line:90%
So gamma i is hermitian.

00:04:13.830 --> 00:04:14.490 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:04:14.490 --> 00:04:16.300 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So is
there supposed to be

00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:20.190 align:middle line:84%
an i in front of
the derivative or do

00:04:20.190 --> 00:04:23.250 align:middle line:90%
we absorb the i into the gamma?

00:04:23.250 --> 00:04:25.800 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So in my
convention, there is no i.

00:04:25.800 --> 00:04:33.670 align:middle line:84%
So with this-- so eta mu mu
here is mostly plus metric.

00:04:33.670 --> 00:04:37.710 align:middle line:84%
So some people, when they use,
say, mostly negative metric,

00:04:37.710 --> 00:04:41.670 align:middle line:90%
then there may be an i in there.

00:04:41.670 --> 00:04:43.860 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so it depends
on your convention

00:04:43.860 --> 00:04:46.110 align:middle line:90%
in defining the gamma matrices.

00:04:46.110 --> 00:04:48.030 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So for minus
plus plus plus, no i--

00:04:48.030 --> 00:04:48.900 align:middle line:90%
OK, sorry.

00:04:48.900 --> 00:04:51.650 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:04:51.650 --> 00:04:52.160 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:53.540 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:04:53.540 --> 00:04:56.420 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, as I mentioned last
time, different conventions

00:04:56.420 --> 00:05:00.230 align:middle line:84%
are annoying, so-- but you just
stick one convention-- should

00:05:00.230 --> 00:05:01.010 align:middle line:90%
be fine.

00:05:01.010 --> 00:05:03.950 align:middle line:84%
Stick to my convention--
would be fine.

00:05:03.950 --> 00:05:04.730 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:05:04.730 --> 00:05:06.605 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Sorry, how can
we get the expression

00:05:06.605 --> 00:05:09.020 align:middle line:90%
for gamma mu dagger?

00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:11.210 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Oh, yeah, this
is just a compact way

00:05:11.210 --> 00:05:13.760 align:middle line:84%
to write down that gamma
0 is anti-Hermitian

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:15.740 align:middle line:90%
and gamma i is Hermitian.

00:05:15.740 --> 00:05:18.350 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, just-- this just compact.

00:05:18.350 --> 00:05:21.020 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, just this is useful so
that you can treat all gamma

00:05:21.020 --> 00:05:23.510 align:middle line:84%
mu in the same way
so that you don't

00:05:23.510 --> 00:05:24.860 align:middle line:90%
have to always separate them.

00:05:24.860 --> 00:05:27.440 align:middle line:90%


00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:28.910 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:05:28.910 --> 00:05:29.930 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:05:29.930 --> 00:05:33.280 align:middle line:90%


00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:36.400 align:middle line:84%
So last time, we
also said you have

00:05:36.400 --> 00:05:41.260 align:middle line:84%
many, many choices for
gamma mu, but they are all

00:05:41.260 --> 00:05:42.890 align:middle line:90%
physically equivalent.

00:05:42.890 --> 00:05:45.490 align:middle line:84%
And so different
choices, they are

00:05:45.490 --> 00:05:47.740 align:middle line:84%
convenient for
different purposes.

00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:52.750 align:middle line:84%
So often we just pick one of
them, and depend on the problem

00:05:52.750 --> 00:05:55.520 align:middle line:84%
we are-- yeah, so that comes
with a little bit experience.

00:05:55.520 --> 00:05:57.940 align:middle line:84%
So for certain problems,
certain choices

00:05:57.940 --> 00:05:59.590 align:middle line:90%
of gamma become more useful--

00:05:59.590 --> 00:06:02.950 align:middle line:84%
become more easier
to manipulate.

00:06:02.950 --> 00:06:05.850 align:middle line:90%


00:06:05.850 --> 00:06:06.360 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:06:06.360 --> 00:06:10.190 align:middle line:84%
So now, let's talk about
the Lorentz covariance

00:06:10.190 --> 00:06:18.635 align:middle line:84%
of the Dirac equation, which we
started a little bit last time.

00:06:18.635 --> 00:06:24.690 align:middle line:90%


00:06:24.690 --> 00:06:29.170 align:middle line:84%
So Lorentz covariance means
that the equation looks the same

00:06:29.170 --> 00:06:32.230 align:middle line:90%
in all Lorentz frames.

00:06:32.230 --> 00:06:35.270 align:middle line:84%
So when you make a
Lorentz transformation--

00:06:35.270 --> 00:06:37.900 align:middle line:90%
so imagine you make a--

00:06:37.900 --> 00:06:38.920 align:middle line:90%
go to another frame.

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:41.650 align:middle line:84%
You start with your frame
defined by this x mu.

00:06:41.650 --> 00:06:45.900 align:middle line:84%
So now, imagine you go to
another frame which you

00:06:45.900 --> 00:06:47.730 align:middle line:90%
make a Lorentz transformation.

00:06:47.730 --> 00:06:51.390 align:middle line:90%


00:06:51.390 --> 00:06:55.320 align:middle line:84%
So the Lorentz covariance
means your equation

00:06:55.320 --> 00:06:59.370 align:middle line:84%
when written in this frame
in terms of x prime mu

00:06:59.370 --> 00:07:01.870 align:middle line:90%
have the same form.

00:07:01.870 --> 00:07:04.200 align:middle line:84%
So last time, we talked
about the scalar equations

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:05.310 align:middle line:90%
at the end.

00:07:05.310 --> 00:07:10.860 align:middle line:84%
And another equation we have
seen before is the Maxwell

00:07:10.860 --> 00:07:15.330 align:middle line:84%
equation, so let me also
very quickly mention

00:07:15.330 --> 00:07:17.370 align:middle line:90%
for the Maxwell equation.

00:07:17.370 --> 00:07:21.880 align:middle line:84%
So when you have a
Maxwell equation,

00:07:21.880 --> 00:07:26.490 align:middle line:84%
which is the story for
the vector potential--

00:07:26.490 --> 00:07:30.190 align:middle line:90%


00:07:30.190 --> 00:07:32.560 align:middle line:90%
so now, in contrast--

00:07:32.560 --> 00:07:34.375 align:middle line:90%
remember for the scalar case--

00:07:34.375 --> 00:07:37.020 align:middle line:90%


00:07:37.020 --> 00:07:40.410 align:middle line:84%
so last time-- let me
just write it down here.

00:07:40.410 --> 00:07:42.780 align:middle line:84%
Last time we said
for the scalar case,

00:07:42.780 --> 00:07:45.690 align:middle line:84%
when you go to a
different frame,

00:07:45.690 --> 00:07:48.270 align:middle line:84%
the phi prime
should be equal to--

00:07:48.270 --> 00:07:51.690 align:middle line:84%
evaluate the new coordinate
should be equal to phi x.

00:07:51.690 --> 00:07:55.360 align:middle line:84%
So this is the transformation
for scalar field.

00:07:55.360 --> 00:07:59.230 align:middle line:84%
But now, if you want to
do Maxwell equation--

00:07:59.230 --> 00:08:03.450 align:middle line:84%
so we have to think about
how this a mu transform

00:08:03.450 --> 00:08:04.920 align:middle line:90%
under Lorentz transformation.

00:08:04.920 --> 00:08:07.260 align:middle line:90%
And now a mu is a vector--

00:08:07.260 --> 00:08:10.800 align:middle line:90%
is a four vector in spacetime.

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:19.090 align:middle line:84%
And so that means that the
a mu should transform also

00:08:19.090 --> 00:08:21.920 align:middle line:90%
as the vector.

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:28.630 align:middle line:84%
So this means that when
you go to a new frame,

00:08:28.630 --> 00:08:39.786 align:middle line:84%
A mu transforms as
lambda mu nu A nu x.

00:08:39.786 --> 00:08:42.620 align:middle line:90%
So here, not only--

00:08:42.620 --> 00:08:47.450 align:middle line:84%
so when A mu evaluate
at new position--

00:08:47.450 --> 00:08:50.870 align:middle line:84%
it can be written as a linear
superposition of the value

00:08:50.870 --> 00:08:53.330 align:middle line:90%
at your original position.

00:08:53.330 --> 00:08:56.175 align:middle line:84%
And this linear
superposition by itself

00:08:56.175 --> 00:08:58.550 align:middle line:84%
is a Lorentz transformation
because the A mu is a vector.

00:08:58.550 --> 00:09:02.670 align:middle line:90%


00:09:02.670 --> 00:09:07.160 align:middle line:84%
And so that means just under
Lorentz transformation,

00:09:07.160 --> 00:09:10.610 align:middle line:84%
the different components
of A mu should also

00:09:10.610 --> 00:09:14.240 align:middle line:90%
change under the transformation.

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:18.950 align:middle line:84%
So given this-- so I
will not show it now.

00:09:18.950 --> 00:09:21.980 align:middle line:84%
Just will take a
couple of minutes,

00:09:21.980 --> 00:09:24.200 align:middle line:84%
but you should
convince yourself--

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:26.880 align:middle line:84%
try to check yourself
that the Maxwell equation,

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:31.760 align:middle line:84%
which can be written--
so for example, as F mu--

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:33.890 align:middle line:90%
mu nu equal to 0.

00:09:33.890 --> 00:09:40.320 align:middle line:84%
This implies that the partial
mu prime in the new frame,

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:44.610 align:middle line:90%
and then the f mu mu prime.

00:09:44.610 --> 00:09:50.010 align:middle line:84%
f mu mu prime is obtained
from this new A mu prime,

00:09:50.010 --> 00:09:52.800 align:middle line:84%
and these two equations
are the same--

00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:53.490 align:middle line:90%
are equivalent.

00:09:53.490 --> 00:09:56.820 align:middle line:84%
Just in one frame, and then when
you go to a different frame,

00:09:56.820 --> 00:09:58.090 align:middle line:90%
then you get this equation.

00:09:58.090 --> 00:10:00.630 align:middle line:84%
So the equation has
exactly the same form,

00:10:00.630 --> 00:10:02.640 align:middle line:90%
but now it's in the new frame.

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:06.160 align:middle line:90%


00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:08.140 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:11.070 align:middle line:84%
So now, let's go
to Dirac equation.

00:10:11.070 --> 00:10:14.730 align:middle line:90%
So now, go to Dirac equation.

00:10:14.730 --> 00:10:19.960 align:middle line:84%
So in the Dirac equation,
again, this psi--

00:10:19.960 --> 00:10:24.440 align:middle line:84%
we need to ask how the
psi should transform

00:10:24.440 --> 00:10:27.560 align:middle line:90%
under Lorentz transformation.

00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:30.570 align:middle line:84%
But now, this psi is a
completely new object.

00:10:30.570 --> 00:10:34.110 align:middle line:84%
So this is not like
in the Maxwell case.

00:10:34.110 --> 00:10:36.030 align:middle line:84%
We know this is a
spacetime vector,

00:10:36.030 --> 00:10:39.080 align:middle line:84%
so you can easily guess
how you should transform.

00:10:39.080 --> 00:10:44.000 align:middle line:84%
So now this psi-- this spinor
space is completely new.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:48.530 align:middle line:84%
So now, we have to figure
out how psi transforms.

00:10:48.530 --> 00:10:51.500 align:middle line:90%


00:10:51.500 --> 00:11:18.270 align:middle line:84%
So let's suppose under a
Lorentz transformation lambda

00:11:18.270 --> 00:11:22.130 align:middle line:90%
that psi transforms as follows.

00:11:22.130 --> 00:11:25.670 align:middle line:90%
Psi prime alpha x prime--

00:11:25.670 --> 00:11:28.550 align:middle line:84%
because now, again, you
evaluate in the new position--

00:11:28.550 --> 00:11:30.200 align:middle line:90%
new frame.

00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:32.750 align:middle line:84%
Since this carries
index, in principle,

00:11:32.750 --> 00:11:34.430 align:middle line:90%
this can be a superposition.

00:11:34.430 --> 00:11:39.320 align:middle line:90%


00:11:39.320 --> 00:11:42.950 align:middle line:84%
You can mix them in
the internal space.

00:11:42.950 --> 00:11:46.130 align:middle line:90%


00:11:46.130 --> 00:11:48.860 align:middle line:84%
In principle, we can
have form like this.

00:11:48.860 --> 00:11:57.980 align:middle line:84%
Say for some matrix S,
which depends on lambda.

00:11:57.980 --> 00:12:00.710 align:middle line:90%


00:12:00.710 --> 00:12:05.120 align:middle line:84%
So in principle, you can have
a transformation like this.

00:12:05.120 --> 00:12:07.430 align:middle line:84%
Say when you evaluate
new position,

00:12:07.430 --> 00:12:09.500 align:middle line:84%
it's given by the value
at the old position,

00:12:09.500 --> 00:12:14.710 align:middle line:84%
but now you can make some
rotations in the internal space

00:12:14.710 --> 00:12:17.410 align:middle line:84%
just as here for
the Maxwell field.

00:12:17.410 --> 00:12:20.650 align:middle line:90%


00:12:20.650 --> 00:12:30.750 align:middle line:84%
So except-- and so suppose this
and then the Lorentz covariance

00:12:30.750 --> 00:12:37.190 align:middle line:84%
would be the statement,
say, for some matrix.

00:12:37.190 --> 00:12:40.000 align:middle line:90%


00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:41.920 align:middle line:84%
And then the Lorentz
covariance then

00:12:41.920 --> 00:12:58.350 align:middle line:84%
is a statement starting
from equation 1--

00:12:58.350 --> 00:13:02.250 align:middle line:84%
you should be able to find
going to the new frame--

00:13:02.250 --> 00:13:07.290 align:middle line:84%
you have an equation like
this-- gamma mu partial mu

00:13:07.290 --> 00:13:17.700 align:middle line:84%
prime minus m psi prime
x prime equal to 0.

00:13:17.700 --> 00:13:20.820 align:middle line:84%
So you should get an identical
equation-- not identical

00:13:20.820 --> 00:13:21.678 align:middle line:90%
equation 2.

