01:03:50.100 --> 01:03:53.730 align:middle line:84%
this all is classical
solutions, and then

01:03:53.730 --> 01:03:55.650 align:middle line:84%
the classical solutions
then become solutions

01:03:55.650 --> 01:03:57.840 align:middle line:84%
to the operator
equations, and then we

01:03:57.840 --> 01:03:59.910 align:middle line:90%
can automatically quantize.

01:03:59.910 --> 01:04:03.810 align:middle line:84%
So then before, we actually
do the quantization.

01:04:03.810 --> 01:04:08.250 align:middle line:84%
It's better we try to find
all the classical solutions

01:04:08.250 --> 01:04:10.380 align:middle line:90%
of Dirac equation.

01:04:10.380 --> 01:04:12.740 align:middle line:84%
And so it's not like a
Klein-Gordon equation--

01:04:12.740 --> 01:04:15.140 align:middle line:84%
we can just immediately
write down the solutions.

01:04:15.140 --> 01:04:18.360 align:middle line:84%
And the Dirac equation is a
little bit more intricate,

01:04:18.360 --> 01:04:23.960 align:middle line:84%
so we need to spend a little bit
of effort to write down the--

01:04:23.960 --> 01:04:27.620 align:middle line:84%
to find all the solutions
of the Dirac equations.

01:04:27.620 --> 01:04:30.110 align:middle line:90%
